ourses about race, the social and moral requirements of American citizenship, and the very nature of American identity. Drawing on such textual sources as studio production files, censorship records, and discussions and debates about religion and film in the black press, as well as providing close readings of films, this richly illustrated and meticulously researched book brings religious studies and film history together in innovative ways.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican Americans in motion pictures. 0aMotion pictureszUnited States. 0aReligion in motion pictures. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aafrican american films.  aafrican american religion.  aafrican american religious practices.  aamerican citizenship.  aamerican film culture.  aamerican film history.  aamerican identity.  acensorship records.  acinema.  acultural studies.  afilm history.  afilm studies.  afilm.  ahistory.  ahollywood studios.  ahollywood.  aindependent filmmakers.  amoral landscape.  amovie history.  amovie studies.  amovies.  arace films.  arace in america.  aracial authenticity.  areligion and film.  areligious.  asound film.  astudio production films.  awartime.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052025100740uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094066640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940666423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520940666/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY